      I would disagree with you that the suspect had split seconds to react to the situation. From what I read this pursuit was multi-jursdictional and the suspect had PLENTY of time to end it peacfully before those final and fatal moments. He CHOSE not to end it but, rather have it ended for him. <br>
<br>
      As for less than lethal ways of dealing with someone, as I sit here now I have the following on my duty belt. <br>
<br>
1) Glock 21 with 40 rounds of .45 auto, 230 grain Ranger XST's (yea, it's lethal). I would point out that the ammunition is sub-sonic so it has less of a chance of penetrating a wall, door, etc. if a stray shot should be fired in an armed conflict.<br>
<br>
2) Collapsable (sp?) Asp Baton. (can be lethal) <br>
<br>
3) Cannister of OC (pepper mace)<br>
<br>
4) While not carried on my belt I also have good training in pressure points and control tactics.<br>
<br>
I also carry with me a Force Continuum which dictates by policy what level of threat can be met with what level of response. I am sure all other depts have this sort of thing. <br>
<br>
Fact is I carry as much less than lethal equipment as I do lethal equipment. I would also add that the OC is used much more often than the baton and is lower on our force continuum because, barring sever allergies, it has less of a chance to be lethal than the baton does and quite franky more easily incapacitates the suspect. <br>
<br>
As far as firearms and the general public are concerned, I won't argue with you, England does it thier way, America does it ours. Apples and oranges.  I will say that while on the job, I have never had any trouble with a legally armed citizen and I gladly accept the increased risk to my health for the right of Americans to bear arms.<br>
